<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-02-22T19:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-02-22T19:45:00-05:00" n="519" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d519">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/7938: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Lane</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-02-22T19:00:00-05:45">February 22, 1934—7
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received 9:41 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>60. President Sacasa told me this afternoon that Congress today declared
                            a state of siege and that none of the local newspapers would be
                            permitted to appear tonight.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>